title: For Sale:  Circa 1885 Ames Company York Rite Templer Sword
postcontent:
I am Selling my 100% authentic Ames Company Knight's Order (Masonic Knights Templar) sword. This sword belonged to the York Rite Knights Templars. In 1857 the Ames Company started marking swords marked ''Ames Co, Chicobee, Mass'', then were bought out by the Henderson Company in 1893, changing to Ames-Henderson, dating this sword between 1873-1893. Research and two appraisals narrows this sword's birth from 1880's-1890's. 
In 2008 representatives of the Antiques Roadshow visited Daytona Beach and shed some light on this artifact. The sword has a remarkable nickel scabbard signifying it was for a Sir Knight. The black handle, which still has the original chain attached, states the owner wasnt an officer.  No one has been able to shed light or information on the acid etching on the blade which leads me to believe it was an uncommon etching used by Ames in the narrow window of time before being bought by Henderson. 
One side depicts a knight holding a religious banner and two knights jousting with the Temple Dome in the background. The opposite side is mainly a floral depiction. The blade is marked with the knight's name, Ernest Alfred Anthony. The sword has it's bumps and bruises but is in amazing condition. The people working for antiques roadshow stated that this sword hasn't been restored. I asked for a number value and they told me it's a high 9 out of 10 and priced this sword just north of $1500. Both appraisals said this sword is in great condition but I believe $1500 is steep for this economy so I would like to ask $500 for the sword as it is well worth it!
I purchased the sword 25 years ago at a reputable antique gallery. While it has been extremely well cared for, it does, as to be expected, have a few cosmetic blemishes. The blade has some minor nicks, but the etching is still very vibrant. The scabbards nickel plating is outstanding with only light surface marks. The black handle, which still has the original chain attached, states the owner was an officer, or among the highest degree within his order. No one has been able to shed light or information on the acid etching on the blade which leads me to believe it was an uncommon etching used by Ames in the narrow window of time before being bought by Henderson. 
One side depicts a knight holding a religious banner and two knights jousting with the Temple Dome in the background. The opposite side is mainly a floral depiction. The blade is marked with the knight's name, Ernest Alfred Anthony. The sword has it's bumps and bruises but is in amazing condition. The people working for antiques roadshow stated that this sword hasn't been restored. I asked for a number value and they told me it's a high 9 out of 10 and priced this sword just north of $2000. Both appraisals said this sword is in great condition but I believe $2000 is steep for this economy so I would like to ask $500-$1000 for the sword as it is well worth it!
My mother purchased the sword for me 25 years ago at an antique gallery. While it has been extremely well cared for, it does, as to be expected, have a few cosmetic blemishes. The blade has some minor nicks, but the etching is still very vibrant. The scabbards nickel plating is outstanding with only light surface marks. It appears not a single scratch is deep enough to scar the scabbard. To my untrained eye it seems to be as good as it gets for its age! The black wooden handle has the most wear with a shallow chip smaller then a dime as well as some minor general wearing of the black paint, most noticeably on the backside opposite the emblem of the cross. 
Again, I'm no expert but those who judged my sword said it's 100% together. It isn't even missing a screw and has the original chain connecting the knights head to the cross on the hilt. I could describe it all day but I will let the pictures talk and can elaborate more if you have any questions. 
This sword is in superior condition compared to all other examples I came across while researching it. 
Placing it's age within a 10 year window is remarkable. 
I'll be sad to hand it over but really wish it goes to someone who can appreciate it more then I can. No one in my family is a Mason so I'd be super happy if it ends up belonging to someone within the order. 
Thanks so much for checking out my item and feel free to contact me with any concerns or questions or information!!!!

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG
postcontent:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

title: For Sale:  Flare Pistol - M2 Aviators Complete Set, RARE
postcontent:
I know the term RARE tends to be overused but here's one I've had for quite a while that really is quite unusual! Let's face it...when was the last time you saw one of these that was a complete and original set come up for sale?

It's a M2 Flare Pistol Aviators Set consisting of the rather massive and super heavy duty US M2 flare pistol (made by International Flare & Signal Company), carry case that holds the flare pistol and it's ammo supply which are 5 absolutely massive MK1 "One Minute" parachute flares. That's right 1 Minute parachutes!! To the best of my knowledge nothing else that is hand held rivals the sheer size and burn duration of these shells. They are monsters and each one weighs over 2 pounds! They are sealed on top and the primers are sealed as well. So while I can't guarantee it - I do think these big boys would fire if you decided to do that. Although you'd certainly need to pick your place well as you might have every emergency responder in the area show up if you don't. 

The flares were made by Kilgore and they are dated 1950. They are consecutively serial numbered so they are an issued matching set. This flare gun outfit might have seen military use or it could have been issued to a commercial flight crew. One thing for sure is that these were in service as the Cold War was heating up.

The pistol, case and the flare cartridges are all in great shape. The carry case has the original nylon carry handle in place, but it is missing the small strap that secures the pistol to the case.

Bottom line is that this is a heck of a find for all those who collect flare guns and related. Give it some consideration as it may be a long time before you'd ever find another.

Thanks for looking.

Price is $575.00 with pickup in the Brandon area or I would consider shipping to the lower 48 where legal at the buyers expense. This set is heavy weighing in at over 20 pounds so shipping could be as much as $30 and possibly a little more depending on your location.

title: For Sale:  7.62x54R Ammo - Russia's Best Sniper & Match Assortment
postcontent:
Here's a 170 total round assortment from my personal collection that represents the best of the best of Russia's Match Grade and Sniper 7.62x54R ammunition from over the last 50 years.

All of this ammo was produced at Novosibirsk Low Voltage Equipment plant (LVE) which is where all of their highest quality ammo is produced. All ammo made at LVE bears the head stamp "188" and the year of production. 

LVE is recognized world wide for their superior quality ammunition. Their Match and Sniper ammunition uses special powders, primers and bullets. Plus much more care is taken producing it. The results speak for them self and you'll be shocked by just how much more accurate this high quality ammo really is. 

Some and quite possibly all of this ammo would be hard to get today and I feel sure that you'd spend more by trying to obtain it from different sources even if you could find it.

Included: (2) still sealed 25 round boxes 182 grain Match Ammo from 1965 - head stamp 188-65. This is loaded in beautiful brass cases with match grade powder, bullets, and primers.

(2) 20 round bundles of 7N1 ammo loaded in annealed copper washed steel cases with a special 152 grain boat tail bullet. Bullet has a steel core followed by a dead air space with a lead knocker in the base. When bullet hits it's target the lead knocker shifts forward destabilizing the bullet resulting in a devastating wound. This ammo was specifically designed for Russian Sniper use with the Dragunov, but it's excellent for Mosins too. Head stamp 188-97.

(2) 20 round boxes 182 grain Extra Match (blue box) ammo from 1971. Ammo is loaded in brass cases with match powder and match grade bullets. It's extremely accurate and has won many matches over the years. Head stamp is 188-71.

(2) 20 round boxes LVE 200 grain Extra Match. This is very hard to find and offers superior accuracy - especially at  ranges over 300 meters. With the 200 grain bullet it's also the hardest hitting 54R available. Head stamp is LVE 10. Many consider this particular ammo as the most accurate production ammunition in the world.

All of this ammo has been stored properly and is in excellent condition. It's all sure to fire and is surprisingly accurate. Again it's becoming increasing difficult to find all of this ammo. The supply of many of these has been exhausted or is no longer being imported.
